    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "idk the 3-2-1 rule sounds a bit vague for us. we already have a backlog, but people just bypass it. how do we actually formalize the process so they can't just sneak things in during the middle of a sprint?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The 3-2-1 rule can be a bit fuzzy, especially when you're working with stakeholders who are accustomed to making changes on the fly. One way to formalize the process is to create a \"change management\" process, where you establish clear guidelines for requesting changes to the project scope. This can include things like a formal change request process, with a clear approval process and a defined timeline for evaluating and implementing changes. You can also consider implementing a \"sprint gate\" review process, where all changes are reviewed and approved before they can be implemented. This can help prevent changes from slipping in during the middle of a sprint.",
      "source": "target",
